<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-728-701  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 728 701.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Office  Dec 1990 v112 n6 p59(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Poor power conditions: how to conquer them.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Finlay, Doug.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Computers and peripherals are only as good as the power they areplugged into, and that is often unstable.andP;  Spikes, overvoltages,line noise, sags, surges, blackouts and brownouts can crash disks,lost or scramble memory and burn out network control units.andO;Fortunately, power problems are easily controlled with standbypower supplies (SPSs), uninterruptible power supplies (UPSs) andsurge protectors.andP;  UPSs, which run constantly, providing aconstant source of energy, are only needed for computers withcritical data.andP;  Minicomputers with as many as 200 users shouldhave UPSs with communications interfaces.andP;  Price for such a systemis about $10,000.andP;  An UPS for a local area network or multiuser,multitasking computer will cost about $3,000 to $7,000.andP;  An UPSfor a single workstation can cost less than $1,000.andP;  Surgeprotectors cost $6.95 to $150; the more sophisticated ones offersuch features as filters that block broadcast radio frequencies.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Uninterruptible Power SupplySurge SuppressorsComputers.andO;Feature:   illustrationcartoon.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>